The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 Ferozepur, March. 2 (PTI): A military court in Punjab today sentenced Major General P.S.K. Chaudhary to one year?s rigorous imprisonment and dismissed him from service. 

 He was found guilty of accepting bribe and committing professional impropriety in the Tehelka arms deal expose. He was sentenced on the basis of the portal?s videotapes that showed him taking Rs 1 lakh and a gold chain.

 Jammu (PTI): The Jammu and Kashmir government has suspended 62 officials for being absent from duty during the ?crisis? period when devastation was wrecked by the snowfall-triggered landslides. The suspended officials were from various departments in Doda and Poonch districts. 

 Karimnagar (PTI): Naxalites shot dead a sarpanch in Andhra Pradesh?s Kurnool district on Wednesday. About 12 rebels went to the house of P. Balwantha Rao, the sarpanch of Mirjampet village, took him out and shot him, the district superintendent of police said. In Karimnagar, seven Maoist rebels and two from the Janashakti group surrendered before police.

 Madurai (PTI): Vigilance officials have arrested a doctor of Srivilliputhur government hospital while accepting a bribe of Rs 300 on Wednesday. The doctor had demanded the money for recommending free scanning for a patient. He was arrested at his clinic, police said.

 New Delhi (PTI): A court on Wednesday granted interim bail to a lawyer who had allegedly cheated investors in his financial firms of Rs 10 crore. Kuldip Mansukhani was granted bail till April 5 after his counsel paid part of the amount in court and submitted that the accused was willing to settle the case.

 Sonepat (PTI): A prisoner committed suicide by hanging himself from a ceiling fan at his house in Khewra village. Bijender, who had been out on parole since the last 10 days, did not come out of his room in the morning. Family members broke open the door to find him dead.

 Jammu (PTI): Nearly 4 lakh devotees braved intense cold and snowfall to visit the Vaishno Devi shrine in the last two months. Nearly 2.5 lakh devotees visited in January and 1,35,727 in February.




